1
00:00:32,440 --> 00:00:37,018
¶ I love your funny face

2
00:00:37,153 --> 00:00:41,020
¶ Your sunny, funny face

3
00:00:41,823 --> 00:00:44,030
¶ For you're a cutie

4
00:00:44,159 --> 00:00:46,235
¶ With more than beauty

5
00:00:46,578 --> 00:00:49,033
¶ You've got a lot of

6
00:00:49,163 --> 00:00:51,120
¶ Personality-N-T

7
00:00:51,248 --> 00:00:55,542
¶ You fill the air with smiles

8
00:00:56,086 --> 00:01:00,748
¶ For miles and miles and miles

9
00:01:00,882 --> 00:01:03,171
¶ Though you're no Mona Lisa

10
00:01:03,301 --> 00:01:05,922
¶ For worlds I'd not replace

11
00:01:06,053 --> 00:01:09,754
¶ Your sunny, funny face

12
00:01:11,683 --> 00:01:19,773
¶ You've made my life so glamorous

13
00:01:20,233 --> 00:01:27,231
¶ You can't blame me
for feeling amorous

14
00:01:27,364 --> 00:01:32,109
¶ Oh, 's wonderful

15
00:01:32,619 --> 00:01:37,530
¶ 'S marvellous

16
00:02:05,316 --> 00:02:07,355
Good morning, Miss Prescott.

17
00:02:09,945 --> 00:02:11,937
Good morning, Miss Prescott.

18
00:02:20,746 --> 00:02:22,988
Now hear this.

19
00:02:40,138 --> 00:02:43,554
I simply cannot release this issue
the way it is.

20
00:02:43,683 --> 00:02:48,345
In the 60 years of Quality
magazine, this hits rock bottom.

21
00:02:48,479 --> 00:02:52,263
If I let this go through, I will have
failed the American woman.

22
00:02:52,399 --> 00:02:54,308
No, Miss Prescott,
don't say that.

23
00:02:54,443 --> 00:02:57,562
The great American woman,
who stands out there naked,

24
00:02:57,696 --> 00:03:00,815
waiting for me
to tell her what to wear.

25
00:03:00,949 --> 00:03:03,071
It doesn't speak.

26
00:03:03,201 --> 00:03:06,700
And if it won't speak to me,
it won't speak to anyone.

27
00:03:07,788 --> 00:03:11,038
A magazine
must be like a human being.

28
00:03:11,166 --> 00:03:13,871
If it comes into the home
it must contribute.

29
00:03:14,002 --> 00:03:17,121
It just can't lie around.

30
00:03:17,255 --> 00:03:19,461
A magazine must have...

31
00:03:20,549 --> 00:03:23,384
..blood and brains and pizzazz.

32
00:03:23,510 --> 00:03:25,004
This is just paper.

33
00:03:25,137 --> 00:03:28,552
If I send paper to the American
woman, I will have let her down.

34
00:03:28,682 --> 00:03:30,923
No, Miss Prescott,
you mustn't say that.

35
00:03:31,059 --> 00:03:33,098
Yes. D for down.

36
00:03:33,227 --> 00:03:34,721
D for dreary.

37
00:03:34,854 --> 00:03:39,232
D for dull and for depressing,

38
00:03:39,359 --> 00:03:41,185
dismal and deadly!

39
00:03:44,697 --> 00:03:47,448
Ahh! Here it is.

40
00:03:47,575 --> 00:03:50,575
Here is our theme.
Here is our answer. Pink.

41
00:03:57,208 --> 00:04:00,826
Girls, girls, girls, girls.
Take this to all the designers.

42
00:04:00,961 --> 00:04:03,250
I want dresses made up in this pink.

43
00:04:03,380 --> 00:04:05,254
Babs, take this to Kaiser Delmont.

44
00:04:05,382 --> 00:04:07,707
I want shoes and stockings
in this colour.

45
00:04:07,843 --> 00:04:10,416
Laura, everything goes pink!

46
00:04:10,553 --> 00:04:13,720
I want the whole issue pink.
I want the whole country pink!

47
00:04:13,848 --> 00:04:18,059
Lettie, take an editorial.
"To the women of America..."

48
00:04:18,185 --> 00:04:20,854
No, make it
"To the women everywhere."

49
00:04:21,188 --> 00:04:22,765
Banish the black,

50
00:04:22,898 --> 00:04:24,440
burn the blue,

51
00:04:24,566 --> 00:04:26,642
and bury the beige.

52
00:04:26,776 --> 00:04:28,650
From now on, girls...

53
00:04:30,571 --> 00:04:34,189
¶ Think pink! Think pink
when you shop for summer clothes

54
00:04:34,325 --> 00:04:38,369
¶ Think pink! Think pink
if you want that quelque chose

55
00:04:38,495 --> 00:04:40,286
¶ Red is dead, blue is through

56
00:04:40,413 --> 00:04:42,205
¶ Green's obscene, brown's taboo

57
00:04:42,332 --> 00:04:46,246
¶ And there is not the slightest
excuse for plum, or puce

58
00:04:46,377 --> 00:04:47,919
¶ Or chartreuse

59
00:04:48,045 --> 00:04:51,710
¶ Think pink!
Forget that Dior says black and rust

60
00:04:51,840 --> 00:04:55,540
¶ Think pink! Who cares
if the new look has no bust?

61
00:04:55,677 --> 00:04:57,669
¶ I wouldn't presume to tell a woman

62
00:04:57,804 --> 00:04:59,262
¶ What a woman ought to think

63
00:04:59,389 --> 00:05:01,879
¶ But tell her if she's gotta think,
think pink

64
00:05:02,016 --> 00:05:04,589
¶ For bags, pink for shoes

65
00:05:04,727 --> 00:05:07,264
¶ Razzle, dazzle and spread the news

66
00:05:07,729 --> 00:05:11,063
¶ And pink's for the lady
with joie de vivre

67
00:05:12,734 --> 00:05:15,485
¶ Pink's for all the family

68
00:05:15,945 --> 00:05:18,815
¶ Try pink shampoo

69
00:05:19,198 --> 00:05:21,274
¶ Pink toothpaste too

70
00:05:21,909 --> 00:05:24,316
¶ Play in pink, all day in pink

71
00:05:24,453 --> 00:05:27,240
¶ Play day in pink

72
00:05:30,041 --> 00:05:30,990
¶ Drive in pink

73
00:05:31,125 --> 00:05:32,156
¶ Come alive in pink

74
00:05:32,293 --> 00:05:35,128
¶ Hang five in pink

75
00:05:37,881 --> 00:05:42,425
¶ Go out dancing
but just remember one thing

76
00:05:42,553 --> 00:05:44,296
¶ You can get a little wink

77
00:05:44,430 --> 00:05:46,138
¶ If you got a little pink

78
00:05:46,265 --> 00:05:49,965
¶ In your swing

79
00:05:52,812 --> 00:05:57,937
¶ Think pink! Think pink,
it's the latest word, you know

80
00:05:59,151 --> 00:06:03,979
¶ Think pink! Think pink,
and you're Michelangelo

81
00:06:05,615 --> 00:06:08,450
¶ Feels so gay, feels so bright

82
00:06:08,576 --> 00:06:11,945
¶ Makes your day, makes your night

83
00:06:12,079 --> 00:06:15,946
¶ Pink is now the colour to which
you gotta switch

84
00:06:16,083 --> 00:06:17,707
¶ To which you gotta switch

85
00:06:17,835 --> 00:06:19,033
¶ Every stitch

86
00:06:19,169 --> 00:06:20,829
¶ Every stitch you switch

87
00:06:20,962 --> 00:06:25,588
¶ Think pink! Think pink
on the long, long road ahead

88
00:06:25,717 --> 00:06:27,127
¶ On the road

89
00:06:27,260 --> 00:06:31,968
¶ Think pink! Think pink,
and the world is rosy red

90
00:06:32,097 --> 00:06:33,591
¶ Everything's rosy

91
00:06:33,724 --> 00:06:36,641
¶ Everything on the great horizon

92
00:06:36,768 --> 00:06:39,010
¶ Everything that you can think

93
00:06:39,771 --> 00:06:42,855
¶ And that includes the kitchen sink

94
00:06:43,399 --> 00:06:44,858
¶ Think pink

95
00:06:44,984 --> 00:06:46,644
¶ Think pink, think pink

96
00:06:46,777 --> 00:06:48,236
¶ Think pink, think pink

97
00:06:48,362 --> 00:06:51,031
¶ Think pink, think pink,
think pink!

98
00:06:54,242 --> 00:06:55,701
Maggie?

99
00:06:56,286 --> 00:06:58,159
Dovitch. I want to see you.

100
00:06:58,287 --> 00:07:01,371
Girls, back to work.
Gentlemen, that will do.

101
00:07:01,499 --> 00:07:04,120
The railroad
is going to paint a whole train pink

102
00:07:04,251 --> 00:07:05,745
and send it on a tour.

103
00:07:05,878 --> 00:07:08,582
TWA will let me know
if we can have a pink plane.

104
00:07:08,713 --> 00:07:12,047
I haven't seen a woman in two weeks
in anything but pink.

105
00:07:12,175 --> 00:07:15,508
- What about you?
- Me? I wouldn't be caught dead.

106
00:07:15,636 --> 00:07:19,468
Dovitch, I can't wait to tell you
about my feature for the next issue.

107
00:07:19,598 --> 00:07:23,180
It's my newest project.
When you hear it, you will drop.

108
00:07:23,310 --> 00:07:25,551
- Now what?
- Just you listen.

109
00:07:25,687 --> 00:07:28,356
Dick Avery
started working on the pictures.

110
00:07:28,481 --> 00:07:30,972
He's more excited about it
than any of us.

111
00:07:31,108 --> 00:07:35,188
Here it is. Clothes for the woman
who isn't interested in clothes.

112
00:07:35,738 --> 00:07:39,153
Marion, give me a long look.

113
00:07:39,282 --> 00:07:40,362
Longer.

114
00:07:40,826 --> 00:07:43,115
Longer.

115
00:07:43,245 --> 00:07:47,243
Steve, tip that back light down
a bit, will you? OK.

116
00:07:48,959 --> 00:07:53,419
Hold it, boys.
Beethoven isn't working. Try Brahms.

117
00:07:53,546 --> 00:07:57,246
Look, Marion,
I'd like to try it again.

118
00:07:57,383 --> 00:08:00,004
This time,
let's see if we can't get with it.

119
00:08:00,135 --> 00:08:03,006
Keep in mind
that you're a woman who thinks.

120
00:08:03,138 --> 00:08:06,008
That is a piece of sculpture
by ltsabuchi.

121
00:08:06,141 --> 00:08:11,098
Look at it as if you understand it.
As if it understands you. See?

122
00:08:14,189 --> 00:08:18,317
No, that's not the way we look
when we're thinking of Itsabuchi.

123
00:08:18,443 --> 00:08:21,397
React to it. Just... say it.

124
00:08:22,822 --> 00:08:25,906
Itsabuchi, hmm?

125
00:08:26,993 --> 00:08:31,072
You haven't quite got it.
Now, listen carefully.

126
00:08:31,205 --> 00:08:34,158
You are in the Museum of Modern Art,
Marion.

127
00:08:34,291 --> 00:08:37,161
Deep, Marion. Profound, Marion.

128
00:08:37,293 --> 00:08:40,413
You have come across this statue.
It says something to you

129
00:08:40,546 --> 00:08:43,037
because you are intellectual,
always thinking.

130
00:08:44,133 --> 00:08:46,339
What are you thinking?

131
00:08:46,468 --> 00:08:49,041
I'm thinking
this is taking a long time,

132
00:08:49,179 --> 00:08:52,678
and I'll never be able to
pick up Harold's laundry.

133
00:08:52,974 --> 00:08:56,177
When Harold doesn't get his laundry,
disaster!

134
00:08:56,310 --> 00:09:01,186
If we don't get this fixed, you may
never see Harold again. Let's go.

135
00:09:01,315 --> 00:09:05,312
The woman who thinks must come
to grips with fashionable attire.

136
00:09:05,444 --> 00:09:09,571
A woman can be beautiful, as well
as intellectual. See facing page.

137
00:09:09,697 --> 00:09:11,108
And how is the facing page?

138
00:09:11,240 --> 00:09:15,238
The facing page looks
as intellectual as a snake.

139
00:09:15,369 --> 00:09:18,121
Nonsense. Marion can be very deep.

140
00:09:18,247 --> 00:09:20,286
Look at her. She's reading.

141
00:09:21,416 --> 00:09:24,536
Marion, dear, what are you reading?

142
00:09:24,669 --> 00:09:26,128
Minute Men From Mars.

143
00:09:27,797 --> 00:09:31,212
Are we all gonna hang around,
or get somebody else?

144
00:09:31,342 --> 00:09:33,879
- How about Lucy Brand?
- On her honeymoon.

145
00:09:34,011 --> 00:09:36,680
- Betty Hayes?
- She's in jail.

146
00:09:36,805 --> 00:09:39,474
Are there no models
who think as well as they look?

147
00:09:39,599 --> 00:09:42,601
Marion might look better
in a different background.

148
00:09:42,728 --> 00:09:45,266
We can go on location.
An intellectual hang-out.

149
00:09:45,397 --> 00:09:47,389
- Somewhere with books.
- A book store.

150
00:09:47,524 --> 00:09:51,189
A sinister place
in Greenwich Village. Come on, girls.

151
00:09:51,319 --> 00:09:55,482
Let's hurry. We might have to pick up
Harold's laundry on the way.

152
00:10:03,038 --> 00:10:04,283
There's one.

153
00:10:05,248 --> 00:10:06,825
Driver, stop here.

154
00:10:06,958 --> 00:10:08,416
That's sinister enough.

155
00:10:11,795 --> 00:10:14,417
Melissa, help me with this lamp.
It's heavy.

156
00:10:14,548 --> 00:10:16,873
I can't, Babs, I got my hands full.

157
00:10:23,389 --> 00:10:27,801
It's movingly dismal. We couldn't
have done better if we'd designed it.

158
00:10:27,935 --> 00:10:30,223
Marion looks smarter already.

159
00:10:34,733 --> 00:10:38,564
I'm sorry. I didn't see you up there.
Are you alright?

160
00:10:40,363 --> 00:10:44,941
Yes, thank you. Can I help you?
Would you like a book?

161
00:10:45,075 --> 00:10:48,942
- Marion, over here.
- Who are those?

162
00:10:50,205 --> 00:10:51,580
May I help you?

163
00:10:51,706 --> 00:10:54,576
Thank you.
We have everything we need.

164
00:10:54,709 --> 00:10:56,666
Please tell me what this is about.

165
00:10:56,794 --> 00:10:59,000
We're just going to take
a few pictures.

166
00:10:59,129 --> 00:11:00,707
What sort of pictures?

167
00:11:00,839 --> 00:11:02,879
- Are you the owner?
- No, Dr Post is.

168
00:11:03,008 --> 00:11:05,296
I work here,
and I'm in charge in her absence.

169
00:11:05,427 --> 00:11:08,131
I'm Jo Stockton. Can you help me?

170
00:11:08,263 --> 00:11:10,338
How do you do? I'm Dick Avery.

171
00:11:10,473 --> 00:11:11,967
What about these pictures?

172
00:11:12,099 --> 00:11:13,724
We want the shop as a background

173
00:11:13,851 --> 00:11:16,520
for fashion pictures
for Quality magazine.

174
00:11:16,645 --> 00:11:20,179
I'm sorry. I can't let you.
Dr Post would never approve.

175
00:11:20,315 --> 00:11:22,557
She doesn't approve
of fashion magazines.

176
00:11:22,692 --> 00:11:26,559
It's chi-chi and an unrealistic
approach to self-impressions.

177
00:11:26,696 --> 00:11:30,313
- We have trouble. She's a thinker.
- She's also a talker.

178
00:11:30,449 --> 00:11:32,276
I must ask you to leave.

179
00:11:32,409 --> 00:11:34,200
We throw ourselves at your mercy.

180
00:11:34,327 --> 00:11:37,447
Haven't poor people like us
a right to make a living?

181
00:11:37,580 --> 00:11:39,537
I asked you to leave.
That is my right.

182
00:11:39,666 --> 00:11:41,243
If the rights of the individual

183
00:11:41,375 --> 00:11:44,162
are not respected by the group,
the group cannot exist.

184
00:11:44,295 --> 00:11:45,494
What does that mean?

185
00:11:45,630 --> 00:11:48,963
"Do unto others as
you would have others do unto you."

186
00:11:49,092 --> 00:11:51,084
We'll only do unto you for a moment,

187
00:11:51,219 --> 00:11:54,634
and it's no more
than we would do unto ourselves.

188
00:11:54,763 --> 00:11:56,886
Girls, I want these books rearranged.

189
00:11:57,015 --> 00:12:00,265
They look too much alike.
They're too pat. Mix them up.

190
00:12:00,393 --> 00:12:02,516
No, you mustn't mix them up.

191
00:12:02,645 --> 00:12:05,219
The books on this shelf
pertain to empiricism,

192
00:12:05,356 --> 00:12:08,974
and on this shelf, materialism,
and on this, psychopiscoparalysm.

193
00:12:09,110 --> 00:12:12,525
Put them back. Please talk to her.
It'll take me hours.

194
00:12:12,654 --> 00:12:15,572
One never talks to Maggie Prescott.
One only listens.

195
00:12:15,699 --> 00:12:19,648
Here. I think we ought to use her
in the shot. Miss, come here, please.

196
00:12:19,786 --> 00:12:22,952
- Me?
- You're selling a book to that girl.

197
00:12:23,080 --> 00:12:24,076
Her?

198
00:12:24,206 --> 00:12:26,531
Just pretend that Marion can read.

199
00:12:26,667 --> 00:12:28,125
Say, listen!

200
00:12:28,252 --> 00:12:29,746
Alright, Marion, let's go.

201
00:12:29,878 --> 00:12:33,294
But this would be a violation
of all my principles.

202
00:12:33,423 --> 00:12:36,210
It would be hypocrisy for me
to lend myself to this.

203
00:12:36,342 --> 00:12:37,753
- I'm sorry, but...
- Shush.

204
00:12:37,885 --> 00:12:41,384
Now, tell Marion about the books
so that we can get out of here.

205
00:12:43,390 --> 00:12:47,304
This deals with epiphenomenalism,
which has to do with consciousness

206
00:12:47,435 --> 00:12:50,389
as a mere accessory
of physiological processes

207
00:12:50,521 --> 00:12:55,432
whose presence or absence
makes no difference...

208
00:12:56,110 --> 00:12:58,149
Whatever are you doing?

209
00:12:58,278 --> 00:12:59,559
Hold it!

210
00:12:59,696 --> 00:13:02,650
- Good. Get her in another outfit.
- Put on the shebop.

211
00:13:02,782 --> 00:13:06,649
None of you seems to realise you're
trespassing on private property.

212
00:13:06,786 --> 00:13:10,320
You run around, ignorant of the fact
that I can have you put in jail.

213
00:13:10,456 --> 00:13:12,994
- For the last time...
- You're getting tiresome.

214
00:13:13,125 --> 00:13:14,536
What are you doing?

215
00:13:14,668 --> 00:13:16,660
Let go. Let go of my arm.

216
00:13:16,795 --> 00:13:20,080
I know you don't mean any harm,
but you are in everyone's way.

217
00:13:20,215 --> 00:13:21,625
Now, we won't be a moment.

218
00:13:22,800 --> 00:13:24,211
Let me in.

219
00:13:24,343 --> 00:13:27,629
The air will do her good.
She was very pale.

220
00:13:36,104 --> 00:13:37,135
Alright, hit it.

221
00:13:37,563 --> 00:13:39,437
Hold it. Ready?

222
00:13:39,565 --> 00:13:41,356
Good. One more, please.

223
00:13:41,484 --> 00:13:43,559
Alright. Hit it.

224
00:13:43,694 --> 00:13:44,773
Hold it. Ready?

225
00:13:45,863 --> 00:13:48,485
Very good, Marion.
One more, please. Last one.

226
00:13:48,616 --> 00:13:49,814
Alright, here we go.

227
00:13:49,951 --> 00:13:51,409
Hit it.

228
00:13:51,535 --> 00:13:53,326
Hold it. Ready.

229
00:13:53,454 --> 00:13:56,123
OK, that's it. That ought to do.

230
00:14:14,389 --> 00:14:16,844
- Quite through?
- Thank you. You've been wonderful.

231
00:14:16,975 --> 00:14:19,216
We'll mention the shop
in the magazine.

232
00:14:19,352 --> 00:14:20,632
Don't you dare!

233
00:14:20,770 --> 00:14:22,596
Taxi!

234
00:14:24,815 --> 00:14:27,057
Oh, no!

235
00:14:29,361 --> 00:14:30,689
Oh!

236
00:14:30,820 --> 00:14:32,231
Hello there.

237
00:14:32,363 --> 00:14:34,486
I stayed to help you
put these back.

238
00:14:34,615 --> 00:14:36,987
I didn't realise we made such a mess.

239
00:14:37,118 --> 00:14:39,655
Which shelf for materialism?

240
00:14:39,787 --> 00:14:42,028
Just hand them to me.

241
00:14:43,332 --> 00:14:45,573
Oh, no.

242
00:14:48,711 --> 00:14:50,585
You should be ashamed of yourself.

243
00:14:50,713 --> 00:14:52,622
We don't usually barge in that way.

244
00:14:52,757 --> 00:14:55,793
I mean a man of your ability
wasting his time

245
00:14:55,926 --> 00:14:58,796
photographing silly dresses
on silly women.

246
00:14:59,721 --> 00:15:03,588
Most people think they're
beautiful dresses on beautiful women.

247
00:15:03,725 --> 00:15:05,966
At most, a synthetic beauty.

248
00:15:07,061 --> 00:15:08,888
Trees are beautiful.

249
00:15:10,939 --> 00:15:13,264
Why don't you photograph trees?

250
00:15:13,400 --> 00:15:16,519
I do what I do for a living.
It has to do with supply and demand.

251
00:15:16,653 --> 00:15:20,068
You'd be amazed how small
the demand is for pictures of trees.

252
00:15:20,198 --> 00:15:22,523
My work is pleasant,
the pay is excellent,

253
00:15:22,658 --> 00:15:24,567
and I get a trip to Paris every year.

254
00:15:24,702 --> 00:15:26,196
I certainly envy you that.

255
00:15:26,328 --> 00:15:29,115
I'd be in Paris now
if I could afford it.

256
00:15:32,083 --> 00:15:33,328
You'd have a ball.

257
00:15:33,460 --> 00:15:35,915
You'd go to a party every night,
drink champagne,

258
00:15:36,045 --> 00:15:39,496
swim in perfume, and a new love
affair every hour on the hour.

259
00:15:39,632 --> 00:15:43,415
If I went to Paris, it would be
to go to Emile Flostre's lectures.

260
00:15:43,552 --> 00:15:45,509
Who goes to Paris for lectures?

261
00:15:45,637 --> 00:15:48,554
Professor Flostre
is the greatest living philosopher,

262
00:15:48,682 --> 00:15:51,090
and father of empathicalism.

263
00:15:51,226 --> 00:15:53,896
Oh? What's empathicalism?

264
00:15:54,604 --> 00:15:59,266
The most sensible approach to
true understanding and peace of mind.

265
00:15:59,400 --> 00:16:00,942
Sounds great, but what is it?

266
00:16:01,069 --> 00:16:02,812
It's based on empathy.

267
00:16:02,945 --> 00:16:05,270
Do you know
what the word "empathy" means?

268
00:16:05,406 --> 00:16:08,323
No, I'll have to have
the beginner's course on that one.

269
00:16:08,450 --> 00:16:10,941
Empathy.
Is it something like sympathy?

270
00:16:11,078 --> 00:16:12,986
Oh, it goes beyond sympathy.

271
00:16:13,121 --> 00:16:15,825
Sympathy
is to understand what someone feels.

272
00:16:15,957 --> 00:16:18,282
Empathy
is to project your imagination

273
00:16:18,417 --> 00:16:22,462
so that you actually feel
what the other person is feeling.

274
00:16:22,588 --> 00:16:25,423
You put yourself
in the other person's place.

275
00:16:25,549 --> 00:16:27,790
Do I make myself clear?

276
00:16:37,977 --> 00:16:40,550
- Why did you do that?
- Empathy.

277
00:16:40,687 --> 00:16:44,637
I put myself in your place and
I felt that you wanted to be kissed.

278
00:16:46,734 --> 00:16:48,940
You put yourself in the wrong place.

279
00:16:49,070 --> 00:16:52,688
I have no desire to be kissed
by you, or anyone else.

280
00:16:52,823 --> 00:16:56,523
Don't be silly. Everybody wants
to be kissed, even philosophers.

281
00:16:57,911 --> 00:17:01,077
I'm sorry, Mr Avery, we don't stock
what you're looking for.

282
00:17:01,206 --> 00:17:02,450
I'll let you out.

283
00:17:02,582 --> 00:17:05,867
Don't bother. I'll throw myself out.

284
00:17:09,671 --> 00:17:10,667
Goodbye.

285
00:17:20,097 --> 00:17:25,257
¶ I was taught that
I ought not expose my inner senses

286
00:17:27,396 --> 00:17:30,811
¶ Had no plan for a man

287
00:17:30,940 --> 00:17:34,226
¶ I was full of self-defences

288
00:17:36,779 --> 00:17:44,738
¶ Now I feel that I really
should face the consequences

289
00:17:45,537 --> 00:17:49,237
¶ My philosophic search

290
00:17:49,374 --> 00:17:54,001
¶ Has left me in the lurch

291
00:17:55,338 --> 00:18:02,087
¶ I must find why my mind
is behaving like a dancer

292
00:18:04,805 --> 00:18:08,304
¶ What's the clue to pursue?

293
00:18:08,683 --> 00:18:14,472
¶ For I have to have the answer

294
00:18:18,067 --> 00:18:23,772
¶ I could cry salty tears

295
00:18:23,905 --> 00:18:30,109
¶ Where have I been all these years?

296
00:18:30,995 --> 00:18:33,237
¶ Is it fun?

297
00:18:33,706 --> 00:18:35,663
¶ Or should I run?

298
00:18:35,791 --> 00:18:41,165
¶ How long has this been going on?

299
00:18:42,672 --> 00:18:48,258
¶ There were chills up my spine

300
00:18:48,969 --> 00:18:54,924
¶ And some thrills I can't define

301
00:18:55,725 --> 00:18:57,967
¶ Does it show?

302
00:18:58,103 --> 00:18:59,894
¶ And who would know?

303
00:19:00,021 --> 00:19:05,181
¶ How long has this been going on?

304
00:19:06,485 --> 00:19:12,071
¶ Oh, I feel that I could melt

305
00:19:12,907 --> 00:19:17,154
¶ Into heaven I'm hurled

306
00:19:18,746 --> 00:19:23,906
¶ I know how Columbus felt

307
00:19:24,626 --> 00:19:30,629
¶ Finding another world

308
00:19:31,257 --> 00:19:36,132
¶ Can I trust how I feel?

309
00:19:37,388 --> 00:19:43,425
¶ Is this my Achilles heel?

310
00:19:44,644 --> 00:19:49,389
¶ Look at me, I'm all at sea

311
00:19:50,649 --> 00:19:57,269
¶ How long has this been going on?

312
00:20:21,803 --> 00:20:24,638
¶ This is grand

313
00:20:24,764 --> 00:20:27,337
¶ This is great

314
00:20:28,393 --> 00:20:36,138
¶ I'm in such a lovely state

315
00:20:38,777 --> 00:20:41,861
¶ Can one kiss

316
00:20:44,198 --> 00:20:47,898
¶ Do all of this?

317
00:21:34,827 --> 00:21:36,784
What do you think?

318
00:21:36,912 --> 00:21:39,319
Good models.
What have you in mind?

319
00:21:39,456 --> 00:21:41,365
A fantastic idea.

320
00:21:41,499 --> 00:21:43,955
It staggers me
nobody's thought of it before.

321
00:21:44,085 --> 00:21:46,754
I'm going to select a girl
to be the Quality Woman.

322
00:21:46,879 --> 00:21:50,462
This girl will represent everything
the magazine stands for.

323
00:21:50,591 --> 00:21:54,090
It's a great gimmick. Any
of these models would be alright.

324
00:21:54,219 --> 00:21:58,134
She's got to be more than alright.
She's got to have pizzazz.

325
00:21:58,265 --> 00:22:02,132
A collection will be designed for her
by the greatest couturier in Paris.

326
00:22:02,269 --> 00:22:04,676
- Paul Duval?
- Yes, Paul Duval.

327
00:22:04,813 --> 00:22:09,059
And he's going to let us photograph
the collection before the opening.

328
00:22:09,192 --> 00:22:11,564
We'll scoop every other magazine.

329
00:22:11,694 --> 00:22:13,900
- Staggers you, doesn't it?
- I can't believe it.

330
00:22:14,029 --> 00:22:18,109
He would be barred
from all the other fashion magazines.

331
00:22:18,242 --> 00:22:22,109
Nonsense. If the project comes off,
we'll all be heroes.

332
00:22:22,245 --> 00:22:26,492
Wait till you see what I've got.
The girl. The Quality Woman.

333
00:22:26,624 --> 00:22:27,787
Oh, Marion's...

334
00:22:27,917 --> 00:22:30,953
Forget her. This is the other girl
I'm talking about.

335
00:22:31,086 --> 00:22:32,995
That thing from the book shop?

336
00:22:33,130 --> 00:22:35,703
Maggie, she's new.

337
00:22:36,174 --> 00:22:37,503
She's fresh.

338
00:22:37,676 --> 00:22:39,253
You've gone out of your mind.

339
00:22:39,385 --> 00:22:42,505
One can't deny that she is unusual.
Who is she?

340
00:22:42,638 --> 00:22:46,422
Don't even ask. The thought of her
makes me shudder. Dreadful girl.

341
00:22:46,559 --> 00:22:48,385
If this is some sort ofjoke...

342
00:22:48,519 --> 00:22:51,970
It's no joke. If we do her over
and fix her up, she'd be great.

343
00:22:52,105 --> 00:22:53,385
She'd devour us all.

344
00:22:53,523 --> 00:22:55,681
- Come on, Maggie.
- Well, look at her.

345
00:22:56,859 --> 00:22:58,816
I think her face is perfectly funny.

346
00:22:58,945 --> 00:23:02,064
The Quality Woman must have grace,
elegance and pizzazz.

347
00:23:02,197 --> 00:23:04,867
This is the first time
I've seen you lack imagination.

348
00:23:04,992 --> 00:23:08,407
Every girl in Quality
has grace, elegance and pizzazz.

349
00:23:08,536 --> 00:23:11,905
What about a girl with character,
spirit and intelligence?

350
00:23:12,040 --> 00:23:14,246
That would be novel
in a fashion magazine.

351
00:23:14,375 --> 00:23:16,332
Sir, I owe you a drink.

352
00:23:16,460 --> 00:23:18,369
Can you make me some enlargements?

353
00:23:18,504 --> 00:23:20,211
- Yes.
- Use our darkroom.

354
00:23:20,339 --> 00:23:23,256
- Let me study the possibilities.
- Now you are talking.

355
00:23:23,383 --> 00:23:26,384
- I'm not promising anything.
- You don't have to.

356
00:23:27,512 --> 00:23:30,845
Runs around here
Iike he owns the magazine.

357
00:23:30,973 --> 00:23:33,464
Lettie, remember that creature
in the book shop?

358
00:23:33,601 --> 00:23:35,308
Get her up here. Order books.

359
00:23:35,435 --> 00:23:38,685
- A large order, so she can't refuse.
- $50 worth?

360
00:23:38,813 --> 00:23:41,351
Yes, $50 worth if necessary.

361
00:23:41,483 --> 00:23:45,811
$50 to get her up here. We'll have to
drug her to get her to Paris.

362
00:23:54,327 --> 00:23:56,996
Er, Miss Prescott, please.

363
00:23:57,122 --> 00:24:00,954
- Lettie, you'd better come out here.
- I've got the books she ordered.

364
00:24:01,710 --> 00:24:04,995
Miss Prescott's secretary
will deal with you.

365
00:24:05,672 --> 00:24:08,542
Oh, it's you. Well, come on in.

366
00:24:09,217 --> 00:24:10,415
Come on.

367
00:24:16,265 --> 00:24:17,759
The books are here.

368
00:24:22,562 --> 00:24:23,760
Come in.

369
00:24:31,653 --> 00:24:35,982
That'll be $52 and 75 cents,
and $1.20 for the taxi.

370
00:24:36,116 --> 00:24:37,942
$53.95.

371
00:24:38,076 --> 00:24:39,867
Drop the books.

372
00:24:39,994 --> 00:24:41,572
Come on, drop the books.

373
00:24:41,704 --> 00:24:43,946
- On the floor?
- Yes, drop them.

374
00:24:46,959 --> 00:24:48,702
Straighten up, shoulders back.

375
00:24:48,835 --> 00:24:52,880
If you girls only knew
how important posture is.

376
00:24:53,006 --> 00:24:55,627
I didn't come here
to enrol in a military school.

377
00:24:55,758 --> 00:24:58,545
All I want is $53.95.

378
00:24:58,677 --> 00:25:00,385
The Modigliani is $12.50,

379
00:25:00,512 --> 00:25:03,846
and the Braque and Hieronymus Bosch
come to $22.75.

380
00:25:03,974 --> 00:25:06,097
$7 for the postimpressionists

381
00:25:06,226 --> 00:25:09,143
and $10.50 for The Egyptians -
Fourth to Seventh Dynasties

382
00:25:09,270 --> 00:25:13,433
make it a total of $52.75,
and there's $1.20 for the taxi.

383
00:25:13,566 --> 00:25:15,973
- Talks incessantly.
- The body's good.

384
00:25:16,110 --> 00:25:18,731
It'll be better
when we get through with it.

385
00:25:18,862 --> 00:25:22,231
- Through with what?
- She might do.

386
00:25:22,365 --> 00:25:23,776
Might do what?

387
00:25:24,701 --> 00:25:26,325
The bones are good.

388
00:25:26,452 --> 00:25:30,070
Suppose we leave my bones alone
and give me my $53.95?

389
00:25:30,206 --> 00:25:32,115
The eyebrows up, a light powder.

390
00:25:32,249 --> 00:25:35,369
I want a little rouge here.
She needs a marvellous mouth.

391
00:25:35,502 --> 00:25:37,993
The hair is awful. It must come off.

392
00:25:38,129 --> 00:25:40,702
Would you mind telling me
what all this is about?

393
00:25:41,174 --> 00:25:44,922
We may as well get started. Babs,
get that dreadful thing off of her.

394
00:25:45,052 --> 00:25:47,757
Now, wait a minute. Just a minute.

395
00:25:47,888 --> 00:25:49,715
Don't! Stop!

396
00:25:50,349 --> 00:25:53,717
This is my second and last encounter
with you lunatics.

397
00:25:53,852 --> 00:25:56,307
You just keep your hands off me,
all of you.

398
00:25:56,979 --> 00:26:00,431
I make a delivery and find myself
being pillaged and plundered.

399
00:26:00,567 --> 00:26:03,770
Well, I'll have no more of it.
I don't want my hair cut.

400
00:26:03,903 --> 00:26:07,237
I don't want my eyebrows up or down.
I want them where they are.

401
00:26:07,365 --> 00:26:12,110
And I see no functional advantage
in a marvellous mouth.

402
00:26:12,244 --> 00:26:15,198
I'm leaving now, and if anyone
makes a move to stop me

403
00:26:15,330 --> 00:26:18,200
there'll be plenty of hair cut,
and it won't be mine.

404
00:26:21,544 --> 00:26:22,824
Bring her back, girls, alive!

405
00:26:29,843 --> 00:26:31,254
Hurry up.

406
00:26:34,556 --> 00:26:36,595
Hurry. Over here.

407
00:26:43,856 --> 00:26:46,525
Hey,
didn't you see that light outside?

408
00:26:47,400 --> 00:26:50,899
In desperation, one does not examine
one's avenue of escape.

409
00:26:51,029 --> 00:26:52,571
Oh, it's you.

410
00:26:55,199 --> 00:26:57,357
I'm sorry if I spoiled a print.

411
00:26:57,493 --> 00:27:01,324
That's alright.
What's all the desperation about?

412
00:27:01,455 --> 00:27:03,162
Those people.

413
00:27:03,290 --> 00:27:06,160
They don't care about
anyone's feelings.

414
00:27:06,918 --> 00:27:09,872
Pulling my clothes
and cutting my hair.

415
00:27:10,004 --> 00:27:13,005
Is that girl in there?

416
00:27:13,132 --> 00:27:15,089
Don't give me away.

417
00:27:15,217 --> 00:27:17,423
Maybe you should give them
a chance...

418
00:27:17,552 --> 00:27:19,675
There was no one here when I came in.

419
00:27:19,804 --> 00:27:21,844
If you see her, hang on to her.

420
00:27:23,766 --> 00:27:25,177
I'll do that.

421
00:27:26,894 --> 00:27:31,223
I'm afraid it's all my fault.
I thought you'd make a good model.

422
00:27:32,316 --> 00:27:33,691
This is your idea?

423
00:27:33,817 --> 00:27:35,726
Yeah, I'm the one you sue.

424
00:27:36,361 --> 00:27:38,400
Oh, how could I be a model?

425
00:27:39,322 --> 00:27:42,773
I have no illusions about my looks.
I think my face is funny.

426
00:27:42,908 --> 00:27:44,486
That's what Maggie said.

427
00:27:44,618 --> 00:27:46,575
I hate to admit it,
but she's right.

428
00:27:46,703 --> 00:27:50,321
What you call funny,
I call interesting.

429
00:27:52,792 --> 00:27:55,544
It's too ridiculous
even to think about.

430
00:27:55,670 --> 00:27:59,370
- I couldn't do it.
- Let me be the judge of that.

431
00:28:00,049 --> 00:28:03,999
I wouldn't take you to Paris
if I didn't think you'd work out.

432
00:28:04,137 --> 00:28:07,303
- Paris?
- Yeah. Look at it this way.

433
00:28:07,431 --> 00:28:09,637
Modelling
may not be as bad as you think.

434
00:28:09,808 --> 00:28:14,019
If it is, you'll be in Paris.
You can see your Professor Whosis.

435
00:28:14,146 --> 00:28:15,770
- Flostre?
- Yeah.

436
00:28:15,897 --> 00:28:18,352
You can talk to him
and go to his lectures.

437
00:28:18,483 --> 00:28:20,522
That way it won't be a total loss.

438
00:28:21,485 --> 00:28:23,312
A means to an end.

439
00:28:23,446 --> 00:28:26,814
Or a means to a beginning,
according to how it works out.

440
00:28:26,949 --> 00:28:28,147
Now, let's see.

441
00:28:29,868 --> 00:28:31,410
There we are.

442
00:28:31,536 --> 00:28:34,537
- Oh, no.
- What's the matter?

443
00:28:34,664 --> 00:28:37,949
How can you possibly
make a model out of that?

444
00:28:38,084 --> 00:28:39,542
You can't be serious.

445
00:28:39,668 --> 00:28:41,910
When I'm done, you'll look like...

446
00:28:42,045 --> 00:28:46,707
What do you call beautiful?
A tree. You'll look like a tree.

447
00:28:47,342 --> 00:28:50,924
¶ Frankly, dear,
your modesty reveals to me

448
00:28:51,054 --> 00:28:53,627
¶ Self-appraisal often makes us sad

449
00:28:54,640 --> 00:28:58,340
¶ And if I add, your funny face
appeals to me

450
00:28:58,894 --> 00:29:01,681
¶ Please don't think
I've suddenly gone mad

451
00:29:02,939 --> 00:29:06,639
¶ You have all the qualities
of Peter Pan

452
00:29:07,360 --> 00:29:13,195
¶ I'd go far before I'd find
a sweeter pan

453
00:29:13,532 --> 00:29:17,660
¶ I love your funny face

454
00:29:19,704 --> 00:29:23,867
¶ Your sunny, funny face

455
00:29:25,960 --> 00:29:29,044
¶ For you're a cutie

456
00:29:29,171 --> 00:29:32,088
¶ With more than beauty

457
00:29:32,215 --> 00:29:39,095
¶ You've got a lot of
personality for me

458
00:29:39,222 --> 00:29:43,930
¶ You fill the air with smiles

459
00:29:44,560 --> 00:29:49,387
¶ For miles and miles and miles

460
00:29:50,690 --> 00:29:53,644
¶ Though you're no Mona Lisa

461
00:29:53,776 --> 00:29:56,777
¶ For worlds I'd not replace

462
00:29:56,904 --> 00:30:00,771
¶ Your sunny, funny face

463
00:31:01,087 --> 00:31:05,167
¶ I love your funny face

464
00:31:07,051 --> 00:31:10,466
¶ Your sunny, funny face

465
00:31:12,347 --> 00:31:15,134
¶ You're not exotic

466
00:31:15,267 --> 00:31:17,971
¶ But so hypnotic

467
00:31:18,519 --> 00:31:20,975
¶ You're much too much

468
00:31:21,606 --> 00:31:25,306
¶ If you can cook the way you look

469
00:31:25,442 --> 00:31:28,941
¶ I'd swim the ocean wide

470
00:31:30,655 --> 00:31:35,281
¶ Just to have you by my side

471
00:31:36,786 --> 00:31:38,992
¶ Though you're no Queen of Sheba

472
00:31:40,331 --> 00:31:43,533
¶ For worlds I'd not replace

473
00:31:54,093 --> 00:31:55,966
¶ Your sunny

474
00:31:57,137 --> 00:31:59,593
¶ funny

475
00:32:00,474 --> 00:32:03,593
¶ face

476
00:32:14,028 --> 00:32:17,646
Ladies, feast your eyes
on our Quality Woman.

477
00:32:17,782 --> 00:32:19,240
Marvellous!

478
00:32:20,826 --> 00:32:23,399
I'm sorry about the trouble.
I didn't realise.

479
00:32:23,537 --> 00:32:27,534
My dear, let me do the apologising.
I behaved abominably.

480
00:32:27,666 --> 00:32:30,203
She's agreed to go to Paris.
She can hardly wait.

481
00:32:30,335 --> 00:32:31,330
Marvellous!

482
00:32:31,461 --> 00:32:35,410
This is not a loss of integrity.
It is a means to an end, and...

483
00:32:35,548 --> 00:32:38,169
There's no time for talking.
Tell us on the plane.

484
00:32:38,300 --> 00:32:42,132
Alright, girls, we've got to
get cracking. To work and to Paris.

485
00:33:38,479 --> 00:33:42,013
- Would you like a tour of Paris?
- No, we're not tourists.

486
00:33:42,149 --> 00:33:44,390
Do we look like people
who gape all day?

487
00:33:44,526 --> 00:33:47,099
They can't understand anyone
coming here to work.

488
00:33:47,237 --> 00:33:50,403
We should all go straight to
our hotels and get some rest.

489
00:33:50,531 --> 00:33:52,773
- I am exhausted.
- I know how you feel.

490
00:33:52,908 --> 00:33:55,446
I'm so tired it's an effort for me
to say I'm tired.

491
00:33:55,577 --> 00:33:58,282
Goodbye.
I'll be in touch.

492
00:34:15,137 --> 00:34:17,046
¶ I want to step out

493
00:34:17,181 --> 00:34:18,805
¶ Down the Champs Elysées

494
00:34:18,933 --> 00:34:20,640
¶ From the Arch of Triumph

495
00:34:20,768 --> 00:34:22,310
¶ To the Petit Palais

496
00:34:22,436 --> 00:34:25,057
¶ That's for me

497
00:34:25,188 --> 00:34:28,723
